<Layout title="Suit Styles Guide - Classic Menswear Chronicle">
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-8">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6">The Comprehensive Guide to Suit Styles</h1>
    
    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507679799987-c73779587ccf?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxwaG90by1wYWdlfHx8fGVufDB8fHx8fA%3D%3D&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1000&q=80" alt="Various suit styles" class="w-full h-64 object-cover mb-6 rounded-lg">
    
    <p class="text-xl mb-6">Understanding different suit styles is crucial for any gentleman looking to build a versatile and stylish wardrobe. This guide will walk you through the most common suit styles, their characteristics, and when to wear them.</p>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">1. Single-Breasted Suits</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">The most common and versatile suit style, single-breasted suits are characterized by a single row of buttons and a narrow overlap of fabric.</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6">
      <li>Typically have one, two, or three buttons</li>
      <li>Suitable for most occasions, from business to formal events</li>
      <li>Two-button suits are the most popular and versatile</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">2. Double-Breasted Suits</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">Double-breasted suits feature two parallel rows of buttons and a wider overlap of fabric.</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6">
      <li>More formal than single-breasted suits</li>
      <li>Usually have four or six buttons, with one or two to fasten</li>
      <li>Create a bold, powerful look</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">3. Three-Piece Suits</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">A three-piece suit includes a matching waistcoat (vest) along with the jacket and trousers.</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6">
      <li>Adds an extra layer of formality and sophistication</li>
      <li>Versatile - can be worn with or without the waistcoat</li>
      <li>Popular for weddings and formal business settings</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">4. Tuxedos</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">The most formal suit style, tuxedos are reserved for black-tie events.</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6">
      <li>Characterized by satin lapels, buttons, and pocket trim</li>
      <li>Typically worn with a bow tie and formal shirt</li>
      <li>Available in both single and double-breasted styles</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">5. Dinner Suits</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">Also known as a smoking jacket, the dinner suit is a slightly less formal alternative to the tuxedo.</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6">
      <li>Often features a shawl collar</li>
      <li>Can be made in various colors and fabrics</li>
      <li>Suitable for formal events that aren't strictly black tie</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Choosing the Right Suit Style</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">When selecting a suit style, consider:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6">
      <li>The occasion or dress code</li>
      <li>Your body type and personal style</li>
      <li>The level of formality required</li>
      <li>The season and climate</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p class="mb-6">For more advice on selecting the perfect suit, check out our guides on <a href="/blog/suit-fabrics" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">suit fabrics</a> and <a href="/blog/mastering-suit-fit" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">mastering suit fit</a>.</p>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Conclusion</h2>
    <p class="mb-6">Understanding different suit styles allows you to make informed choices when building your wardrobe. Whether you're dressing for a business meeting, a wedding, or a black-tie gala, knowing the characteristics and appropriate uses of each suit style will ensure you always look your best.</p>
    
    <p>For more in-depth information on specific aspects of suiting, explore our <a href="/blog" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">blog</a> and other <a href="/guides" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">style guides</a>.</p>
  </article>
</Layout>